The paper discusses program synthesis, which involves automatically generating code that satisfies a given specification. This falls under the category of automated reasoning, which is typically associated with logic and theorem proving. Therefore, cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) is a likely sub-category. The paper also discusses using SMT solvers, which are commonly used in program verification and constraint solving. This suggests that cs.PL (Programming Languages) and cs.SE (Software Engineering) are also likely sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses syntax restrictions on generated solutions, which falls under the category of formal languages and grammars, suggesting cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory) as a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper presents experimental results, which suggests that cs.SC (Symbolic Computation) may also be a relevant sub-category.
